06169nam a22009855i 9783110591972DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105919727 a10.1515/97831105919722doi  a(DE-B1597)493532  a(OCoLC)1049643549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB438b.K35 2018 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a1602231 aKalbarczyk, Alexander, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPredication and Ontology :bStudies and Texts on Avicennian and Post-Avicennian Readings of Aristotle’s ›Categories‹ /cAlexander Kalbarczyk. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (XI, 344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScientia Graeco-Arabica ,x1868-7172 ;v2200tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of contents -- tIntroduction -- tKey issues in ibn sīnā’s reception of the categories and in the ensuing philosophical debates -- t1. varying approaches of determining the scope of the categories -- tA. study -- tB. texts -- t2. ibn sīnā’s reception of the two aristotelian criteria for dividing “beings” (ὄντα): “being said of a subject” and “existing in a subject” -- tA. study -- tB. texts -- t3. attempts at providing a systematization of the scheme of ten categories -- tA. study -- tB. texts -- t4. disputes about the conceptual unity and generic predicability of accident and substance -- tA. study -- tB. texts -- tSummary and conclusion -- tAppendices -- tBibliography -- tIndices0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Predication and Ontology A. Kalbarczyk provides the first monograph-length study of the Arabic reception of Aristotle’s Categories. At the center of attention is the critical reappraisal of that treatise by Ibn Sīnā (d. 428 AH/1037 AD), better known in the Latin West as Avicenna. Ibn Sīnā’s reading of the Categories is examined in the context of his wider project of rearranging the transmitted body of philosophical knowledge. Against the background of the late ancient commentary tradition and subsequent exegetical efforts, Ibn Sīnā’s Kitāb al-Maqūlāt of the Šifāʾ is interpreted as a milestone in the gradual reshuffle of the relationship between logic proper and ontology. In order to assess the philosophical impact of this realignment, some of the subsequent developments in Ibn Sīnā’s writings and in the emerging post-Avicennian tradition are also taken into account. The thematic focus lies on the two fundamental classification schemes which Aristotle introduces in the treatise: the fourfold division of Cat. 2 ("of a subject"/"in a subject") and the tenfold scheme of Cat. 4 (i.e., substance and the nine genera of accidents). They both pose the question of whether and how the manner in which an expression is predicated relates to extra-linguistic reality. As the study intends to show, this question is one of the driving forces of Ibn Sīnā’s momentous reform of the Aristotelian curriculum. This monograph has been awarded the Iran World Award for Book of the Year (2020).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCategories (Philosophy). 0aIslamic philosophyxGreek influences. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aOntology. 0aPhilosophy, Arab. 0aPredicate (Logic). 4aArabische Ontologie. 4aAristoteles /Kategorien. 4aAvicenna. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aArabic ontology.  aArabic philosophy of language.  aAristotle's Categories.  aAvicenna.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2018 Part 1z978311076248808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK P